The Macedonians vote in a referendum to change their country's name
On Sunday, the Macedonians voted in a referendum to change the name of their country to the Republic of North Macedonia. This movement would allow a ten-year dispute with Greece to be resolved, which blocks the country's efforts to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece, where the historic country of Macedonia is located, maintains that the name of the northern neighbour constitutes a claim to its territory and has therefore vetoed the accession of the country to the EU and NATO.
In June, the governments of both countries reached an agreement on naming, but nationalists say that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority in Macedonia.
President Ivanov said he would not participate in the vote. The campaign encouraging the boycott raised doubts as to whether attendance would reach the minimum level of 50% required to declare the referendum binding.
The referendum asked the following question: "Do you support joining NATO and the EU following the adoption of an agreement with Greece".
Supporters of the change of name, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaew, say that it is worth paying the price for the possibility of joining Macedonia – one of the countries formed after the collapse of Yugoslavia – to organisations such as the European Union or NATO.
"I voted in favour of the future of my country so that young people in Macedonia could live free under the umbrella of the European Union. EU membership will provide us all with greater security," said 79-year-old Oliver Georgievska of Skopje.
Although the referendum is not legally binding, a sufficient number of parliamentarians have declared that they will respect the results of the vote.
A change of name requires the support of two thirds of the members of parliament.
The state electoral committee reported that no unusual events had been reported by 13 o'clock.
However, attendance at this hour was only 16% compared to 34% in the last 2016 parliamentary election. At that time 66% of the eligible people voted.
"I voted for my children. Our place is in Europe," said 62-year-old Tanewski, a Skopje voter.
On 30 September 2018, in the town of Strumica, Macedonia, the Prime Minister of the country Zoran Zaew, his wife Zorica and son Duszko voted in a referendum on changing the country's name to open the way to membership of NATO and the European Union.
In front of the parliament building in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kawardarkov prepared a small scene and placed chairs in front of tents spread by the boycotting people of the referendum.
"We support membership of NATO and the EU, but we want to join these organisations with a head high rather than a back door," Kawardarkow said.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they do not want us as Macedonia, we can turn to other countries, such as China or Russia, and become part of the Eurasian integration."
Prime Minister Zaew says that NATO membership will bring the necessary investments to Macedonia, with unemployment rates of more than 20%.
"I believe that a large majority will advocate a change of name in a referendum, as 80% of citizens support the European Union and NATO," Zaew said after giving his vote.
He stated that the "yes" vote was a "confirmation of our future".
In a poll published last Monday by the Macedonian public research institute from 30 to 43% of voters declared their willingness to participate in the referendum, which is less than the required attendance.
According to another poll conducted by Macedonian TV Telma TV, 57% of respondents plan to vote in a Sunday referendum.
70% of those surveyed said they would support the name change.
In order for the vote to be successful, attendance must be 50% + 1 vote.
Failure in the referendum would be the first major blow to the pro-Western government policy since taking power last May.
