John Edward: Language skills necessary for the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland continue to enjoy their scientific achievements — in 2018 they could boast further excellent exam results, supported by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music, and other social activities.
The schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) attended by more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland seek to provide the best level of service provided to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, their career path and to indicate their role as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector with the opportunity to develop and implement a school-specific curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said: “If you speak to another man in a language he understands, then it goes into his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
This is a clear reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the final exam this year show that languages are ranked first in league rankings, with the highest rates of reporting occurring in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a higher A rating.
Data from 74 SCIs member schools showed that 72 percent of students obtained a higher A rating in Mandarin, and 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners, and 63 percent of Spanish learners also obtained an A rating.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, language learning, as subjects of choice, is carried out in the same field as STEM learning (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) as part of curricula in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills showed that the reason for the difficulties in hiring employers in 17 percent accounted for the lack of language skills of candidates.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people for a career.
These skills are essential in a globalised world with a growing number of jobs requiring knowledge of languages,
Life - long skills, such as learning a second language, will provide a great advantage in the future, regardless of the path of professional development.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person in relation to competition.
According to the 2013 YouGov poll, which involved over 4000 adults of the British, 75% of them were unable to speak in a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and the French language was the only language whose percentage of people spoke was double-digit, i.e. 15%.
That is why investing in teaching foreign languages is so important for today's children.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of the developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding adequate employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ in terms of its languages.
Many schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered to be the most important for the UK in 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the child's interest, in independent schools there will always be many languages to choose from that will be taught by teaching staff specialised in this area.
Scottish independent schools are involved in creating a teaching environment that prepares their children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed — no matter what their future is.
At present, it cannot be denied that in an international business environment languages are still crucial for the future of the country, and so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a large choice, variety and level.
It's just the right thing to do.
John Edward, Chairman of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
