North Korea says "strongly no" to unilateral disarmament without trust.
The North Korean Foreign Minister said on Saturday during a speech at the United Nations that the lack of abolition of sanctions only exacerbates North Korea's lack of confidence in the United States and there is no way that the country unilaterally resigns from nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho said at the Annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant measures of goodwill" last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test sites, and a commitment to non-proliferation of weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see any specific response from the US," he said.
"Without trust in the United States there will be no guarantee of our national security and under such circumstances there will be no unilateral disarmament of North Korea".
While Ri repeated the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's reluctance to a "staged" approach to denucleation, in which North Korea would be rewarded for gradually taking action, his statement seemed significant as it did not reject unilateral denucleation as it had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between the President-in-Office of the United States and the leader of North Korea, held on 12 June in Singapore, when Kim Jong Un pledged to work for the "denuculating of the Korean Peninsula", and Trump promised guarantees of North Korea's security.
North Korea expected the formal end of the Korean War (1950–1953), but the United States delegation announced that Pyongyang had to give up nuclear weapons first.
Washington also resisted calls to mitigate severe international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on "denuclearisation in the first place" and increases the pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a forced manner, even opposing the signing of the "declaration of the end of the war", Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can put us on our knees is a dream of people who behave in an ignorant way toward us.
The problem, however, is that the lack of abolition of sanctions exacerbates our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, which was discussed by the United States leader at the UN at the beginning of the week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months, after which he added: "If the party to the denucleation issue were South Korea and not the United States, then there was no impasse in the denucleation of the Korean Peninsula".
Mim this, the tone of Ri's speech was completely different compared to the previous year, when he said at the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea's missiles in the United States was inevitable after "Mr Evil President" Trump (Mr. Evil President Trump) called Kim Jong Una "rocket man" (a man rocket) on a suicide mission.
This year, at the UN Trump, which last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, he praised Kim Jong Un for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but also said that much work was still needed, and also stated that until North Korea was deprived of nuclear weapons, sanctions would not be lifted.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not set a time frame for it, saying, "Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia claim that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said on Thursday at the UN Security Council that: "The enforcement of the sanctions of the Security Council must continue and be continuous until we find full, final and verified denuclearisation."
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea, attempting to choke funding for Pjongjangu's nuclear program and ballistic missiles.
