He stated that Kim Jong Un had told him that the "adequate measures" he wanted were security guarantees that Trump had committed himself to in Singapore, and that he had taken steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course for a proper rest period
A new course at Harvard University this year provided all students with more sleep to combat the growing macho culture of learning by "all-night caffeine-driven students".
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea of the basis for taking care of themselves.
Charles Cheisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create a course by giving a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on science.
"When the speech was finished, one girl came to me and said, "why is it only now that I'm in my senior year?"
She stated that no one had ever told her the meaning of the dream, which surprised me," said The Telegraph.
During the course, which took place for the first time this year, it is explained to students how good sleeping habits help to achieve good results in science and sport, as well as improve the overall well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university health service, said that the course was decided to introduce after it was stated that students had suffered severe sleep deprivation within a week.
An hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section includes an image of the dorm room where students click on coffee cups, curtains, exercises and books to get information about the impact of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects sports results, as well as how important it is to preserve the regularity of sleep.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We know that this will not cause an immediate change in student behaviour.
But we believe that they have the right to know — just as they all have the right to know what health effects smoking carries”, added Professor Cheisler
The culture of pride from “all-night learning” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students means an increasing problem of sleep deprivation.
Providing enough sleep of good quality should be a "secret weapon" of students combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety, or even avoiding gaining weight, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into hunger mode, making the student constantly hungry," he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Cheisler develop a course after taking part in one of his classes last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the introduction of a course for the entire campus.
The next step according to him is to ask all students of postgraduate studies to complete a similar program of study before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Cheisler recommended that students set an alarm reminding when to go to sleep and when to get up, and that they be aware of the harmful effect of the "blue light" emitted by electronic devices and LED lighting, which can upset the daily rhythm and cause problems with falling asleep.
