A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to “see” hostile cells.
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to “see” enemy cells and destroy them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize enemy cells as part of treatment.
This method involves separating immune cells from the patient and changing them in the laboratory.
Then they can “see” a protein common to many cancers. Then they are re-injected into the body.
The trial vaccine shows promising results in patients with various types of cancer.
In one woman treated with a vaccine teaching the immune system, the loss of ovarian cancer was observed for more than 18 months.
The method is to separate immune cells from the patient, change them in the laboratory so that they can “see” a protein common to many cancers called HER2 and then re-inject these cells.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the American National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland said: "Our results indicate that the vaccine is very promising".
HER2 "powers the growth of several types of cancers", including breast, ovarian, lung and colon cancer, explained Prof. Berzofsky.
A similar approach of taking immune cells from patients and "teaching" their location of cancer cells worked to treat some kind of leukemia.
