HIV/Aids: China has a 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of people living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people affected by this problem are reported by healthcare professionals in the country.
Only in the second quarter of 2018, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of new cases were transmitted by sex, which means a change in relation to the past.
Traditionally, HIV spreads rapidly in some parts of China as a result of blood transfusions.
However, the number of people infected with HIV has been almost completely reduced, as Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 compared to one year.
The transmission of HIV by the sexes is a serious problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminated in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is common.
Given the country's conservative values, research estimates that 70–90% of men having sex with men will eventually marry a woman.
Many cases of disease transmission are due to insufficient protection when having sex in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has provided widespread access to HIV drugs as part of its efforts to tackle this problem.
