The Global Citizen Festival, which was launched in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international group of activists to fight poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket for this event (unless it was decided to purchase a VIP ticket), the concert participants had to perform a number of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, sending an email to the world leader, making a phone call or other significant activities to help raise awareness about the goal of eliminating poverty.
But what successes can Global Citizen boast over the 12 years remaining to achieve his goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a good way to convince them to require action, or another case of so-called "clitivism" when people feel they are doing something important by signing an online petition or posting an entry on a tweeter?
Global Citizen claims that since 2011, it has recorded more than 19 million "actions" of people supporting the action, aiming to achieve many different objectives.
He also argues that these actions helped to stimulate global leaders to declare commitments and regulations worth over $37 billion that are expected to affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements resulting from its activities, under which at least $10 billion has already been paid or financed.
The group estimates that the funds secured so far have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a British investor partnership and realtors involved in "helping children to reach their full potential", which promised to hand Rwanda $35 million to help with the elimination of malnutrition in the country, after members of Global Citizen sent over 4,700 tweets.
"With the support of the British government, donors, national governments and members of the Global Citizen, such as you, we can make social injustice, such as malnutrition, into history" — Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of Power of Nutrition, during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after implementing more than 5,000 actions calling on Britain to improve the quality of nutrition for mothers and children, the government announced funding for the Power of Nutrition project, which will reach up to 5 million women and children with nutritional problems.
For one of the most frequently asked questions on its website, which read, "How can you be sure that extreme poverty will be eradicated?",
Global citizen replied: “It will be a long and difficult road — sometimes we will stumble and fail.
But as with the once great civil rights movement and the fight against apartheid, we will succeed because together we are stronger.
