The creator of the World Wide Web network plans to launch a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook platforms.
Tim Berners-Lee, the creator of the World Wide Web network, launches a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google platforms.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company based on an open source platform — Solid — owned by Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and what people have access to specific information.
In an exclusive interview for Fast Company Berners-Lee, he joked that the purpose of the creation of Inrupt was to "dominate the world."
"We have to do it now," he said, referring to the startup.
"An historic moment has come".
The application uses Solid platform technology to allow people to create their own "webshop with personal data" or otherwise POD.
It may contain contact lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify available in one browser and at the same time.
The unique feature of an online store with personal data is that it is entirely up to the user who has access to what information.
The company calls it "personal power of attorney through data".
According to the company's president, John Bruce, the idea of Inrupt is to provide resources, processes and appropriate skills to help make the Solid platform available to all people.
Currently, the company consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers employed to work on the project and a volunteer programmers community.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world could create their own decentralised applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to “Facebook and Google about whether to make a complete change that will turn all their business models upside down overnight.
"I don't ask them for permission."
In a medium post published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to provide commercial energy and ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid platform".
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has contributed a lot to the debate on net neutrality.
Calling to life the Inrupt Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am extremely excited to think of the next era in network development," added Berners-Lee.
