The memory of the only clergyman Church of England, who during World War I was awarded the Victoria Cross, was celebrated 100 years later in his hometown.
Reverend Bishop Bernard Vann was decorated on 29 September 1918 for attacking Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was killed by a sniper four days later, never knowing that he had been awarded the highest British military order.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren unveiled a memorial stone during a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Vann, said that the unveiling of the stone exactly on the centenary of his grandfather's recognition was "a uniquely symbolic character."
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal "in a very dense fog and under heavy fire from field guns and machine guns".
He then rushed into the line of fire and led it forward with “the greatest courage” and then single-handedly launched an attack on the field division, disposing of three of them.
Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918 — a little over a month before the war ended.
Michael Vann (72 years old) said that his grandfather's actions were "something I could never face, but at the same time something humble."
Along with his brother, Dr. James Vann, he laid a wreath after the end of the parade led by Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said that he felt "very honored to attend the parade" and added that "the courage of the true hero is manifested in the support he receives from many people."
