National Trust eavesdropping on the secret life of bats
New research carried out on the estate in the Scottish Highlands area aims to show how bats use the landscape when gaining food.
Research results are expected to shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help to focus future efforts to protect them.
Research conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will concern common dwarfs and minor ones, as well as brown bats with long ears and bats in the family of redheaded nocturnes at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be deployed in key locations around the estate for the full-season tracking of bat activity.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out field studies using portable detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings is intended to determine the frequency of signals sent by bats and how individual species behave.
A habitat map and report will then be developed to create a detailed picture of their landscape-scale behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a conservation advisor at the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best ways to maintain forest areas for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have decreased significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development works that affect the girdles and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can also pose a threat, as can fly traps and some chemicals used in building materials, and even domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their hunting habits at night, their ears are more helpful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a complex technique of echolocation to search for worms and obstacles in their path.
The NTS organization, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bats very seriously.
It consists of ten trained experts who regularly conduct tests, inspections of the grows, and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization even established the first and only dedicated bat reserve in Scotland at the Three Estates in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten Scottish bat species.
David Thompson, the estate manager, says it is ideal for bats territory.
"Three has a great area for bats," he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and excellent habitats.
However, there are still many unknowns about bats. The work we do here and in other estates will help us to better understand what they need to develop."
It highlights the importance of bat control before proceeding with maintenance work in the estates, as the unintentional destruction of one gherkins can kill up to 400 females and young, which could lead to the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected — killing, harassing, or disturbing them, and destroying their girdles is illegal.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to provide assistance.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and in the case of many species we don't even know how their populations are doing."
