To carry out an attack that took place in October on a bike path running along the West Side Highway in Lower Manhattan, thirty-year-old Saipov allegedly used a rented Home Depot truck that was run over by pedestrians and cyclists on his way.
According to a notification in the southern district of New York about the intention to demand the death penalty to justify its necessity, prosecutors will have to prove that Saipov "intendedly" killed eight victims and "intendedly" caused serious injuries to the body.
According to the court document, both of these charges are punishable by the death penalty.
A few weeks after the attack, the federal jury presented Saipov with an indictment covering 22 positions, including eight counts of murder in illegal activity — which is usually followed by federal prosecutors in matters of organized crime — and a charge of violence and destruction of motor vehicles.
According to prosecutors, the organization of the attack required "solid planning and reflection". The way Saipov conducted it, they described it as "monster, cruel and immoral".
"Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov brought harm, harm and loss to Diego Enrique Angelini's family and friends, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucca," states a notice of intent.
Five of the victims were citizens of Argentina who stayed in New York City for tourism.
The last time a death penalty was filed in the southern district of New York City ten years ago.
The accused Khalid Barnes was found guilty of murdering two drug dealers, but eventually in September 2009 he heard a life sentence.
The death penalty as a result of a federal case was last executed in New York City in 1953 on Julius and Ethel Rosenberg. The marriage was lost after two years earlier they had been found guilty of conspiracy and espionage to the Soviet Union during the Cold War.
Both Rosenbergs were executed in an electric chair on June 19, 1953.
According to Saipov's court documents, which came from Uzbekistan, he showed no remorse within months of the attack.
Police say he told investigators he was comfortable with what he did.
According to the indictment, Saipov confessed to the authorities that he was inspired by the ISIS films he watched on the phone.
According to the police, he also demanded that the ISIS flag be displayed in his hospital room.
On the indictment of 22 counts, he answers that he is innocent.
David Patton, one of the federal public defenders who represent Saipov, said that they are "for obvious reasons disappointed" by the prosecutor's decision.
"We believe that the decision to demand the death penalty and to reject life without the possibility of early release after admitting guilt will only prolong the suffering that these events have brought upon all the persons concerned," he said.
Saipov's defense team had previously asked prosecutors not to demand the death penalty.
