What the benefits of the economic war between the United States and China can bring to Beijing
The volleys starting the economic war between the US and China were stunning and although the battle is still ongoing, in the long term the conflict between these countries may be beneficial to Beijing, say experts.
The first warning was fired this year by the President of the United States, Donald Trump, imposing duties on China's key export goods, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation occurred this week after the introduction of new tariff rates on goods worth $200 billion (£150 billion), which resulted in the taxation of half of all goods arriving in the US from China.
Each time Beijing reciprocated in nature, recently raising tariffs on US goods worth $60 billion from five to ten percent.
China is determined to respond to every US strike, and it does not appear that the second economy in the world is about to step down.
Obstructing Washington to withdraw means accepting demands, but a public bow before the United States would be too embarrassing for China's president, Xi Jinping.
However, according to experts, if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressure from the U.S. trade war could strengthen China in the long term, reducing the dependence between the two economies.
"The fact that a quick political decision taken in Washington or Beijing could create conditions to unleash economic chaos in one of the countries is in fact much more dangerous than the observers have so far admitted," said Abigail Grace, a researcher dealing with Asia at the think tank Center for New American Security.
According to the Minister of Foreign Affairs, Syria is “ready” for the return of refugees
The government claims that Syria is ready for the voluntary return of refugees, and asks for help in rebuilding a country ruined as a result of over seven years of war.
In his speech to the UN General Assembly, the Syrian Foreign Minister, Walid al-Moual, stated that the conditions in the country were improving.
"The situation in our territory is now more stable and secure thanks to progress in combating terrorism," he said.
In an effort to restore normality, the government continues to rebuild areas destroyed by terrorists.
All the conditions have already been fulfilled so that refugees who had to leave the country because of terrorism and unilateral economic moves aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods can return voluntarily.
According to UN estimates, since the beginning of the war in 2011, more than 5.5 million citizens have left Syria.
Another six million people who still live there need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian regime would be happy to receive assistance in rebuilding the destroyed country.
However, he stressed that he would not accept aid under conditions or offered by the countries that sponsored the rebellion.
