Information about the flower — in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota the density of plankton decreases
The latest Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission report shows an overall decline in plankton density in some parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, the presence of a grumpy flower was reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting that its densities were decreasing.
It extends about 209 kilometres [209 km] of the coastline, from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The blooms can be encountered about 16 kilometres from the Hillsborough County coast, but compared to the previous week in a smaller number of places.
The flower was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, there was an average concentration of plankton off the coast and in Pinellas County waters, low to medium off the Hillsborough County coast, natural to high in Manatee County, natural to high off the coast and Sarasota County waters, natural to medium in Charlotte County, natural to high off the coast and Lee County waters, and low in Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Last week, however, they were not reported in northwestern Florida.
